[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]Oil &amp; Gas UK[bold]Introduction[bold]Oil &amp;
[normal] Gas UK is the principal trade association for the offshore oil and gas exploration and production industry in the United Kingdom, with more than 370 member companies, comprising oil and gas operators and investors and a broad spectrum of the supply chain:
[normal] contractors, suppliers, law firms and consultants.  We 
[normal]w
[normal]elcome
[normal] the opportunity to respond to 
[normal]this
[normal] 
[normal]Business, Innovation and Skills Committee
[normal]’s 
[normal]inquiry into the Extractive Industries Sector.
[normal]As a trade association for the UK’s offshore oil and gas industry,
[normal] our answers will be in this context and will not include information on the UK extractive industry more widely.
[normal] Further, we have only answered the questions which we are in a position to provide information.
[normal]The UK’s offshore oil and gas industry paid c£6.5bn in production taxes in 2012-2013, and UK
[normal] 
[normal]C
[normal]ontinental 
[normal]S
[normal]helf (UKCS)
[normal] production supports the UK’s Balance of Trade by c£32bn per year.
[normal] 
[normal]In addition to this, the wider oil and 
[normal]gas supply chain is estimated to have paid 
[normal]a further 
[normal]£5bn in corporation and payroll tax.
[normal] 
[normal]Capital investment in new fields in 2013 alone will rise to a record £13.5bn. Total capital investment committed to projects already in production or under developme
[normal]nt totalled £44bn at the start of 2013, £13bn higher than 12 months earlier.
[normal]Indeed, whilst subdued production and record investment have driven tax revenues down in the short-term, the contribution from oil and gas production was still over 15 per cent of
[normal] the Exchequer’s total receipts of corporation tax.
[normal]The
[normal] UK oil and gas
[normal] industry support
[normal]s
[normal] some 450,000 jobs, many of which are highly skilled, across the whole economy. Of these, 36,
[normal]000 are employed by operating companies 
[normal](12,500 of whom work
[normal] offshore); 200,000 are employed in the supply chain (45,000
[normal] of whom work offshore); 112,000 in jobs induced by the economic activity of the above employees, and; 100,000 in the export of goods and services.
[normal]As mentioned above, related exports from the UK’s oil and gas industry support some 100,000 jobs, with £7bn of the supply chain’s £27bn contribution to the UK economy being 
[normal]made up o
[normal]f exports. The UK’s subsea engineering sector is a world leader, capturing 45 per cent of the global market.
[normal]The recent 
[normal]Scottish Council for Development
[normal] and
[normal] Industry’s 2011-12 Survey of International
[normal] 
[normal]Activity in Scotland’s Oil a
[normal]nd
[normal] 
